We've said a lot about forgiveness in other topics: &quot;Persecution&quot; for
one.

I'm thinking that word gets tossed around a lot without people
considering what it's about. If I ask someone to forgive me, for
example, that means I'm acknowledging I did something wrong. If I ask
someone to forgive me and it doesn't mean I've acknowledged my
wrong-doing, I need to use another word.

Same goes for when I forgive someone. When I forgive someone that
means I'm acknowledging that someone has done something wrong TO me.
How many times do we flippantly say, &quot;I forgive you,&quot; without
considering that we've actually been wronged.

&quot;I forgive you,&quot; when said flippantly, is at times a way to avoid the
reality of the situation. Many times I'll ask a person who says that,
&quot;What did the person do wrong.&quot;&quot;How were you harmed by that person.&quot;
No answer - or - long pause.

When we get in touch with how we've been harmed instead of running to
&quot;I forgive you,&quot; we will get in touch with pain. Anger, sadness, fear,
etc. may be our reaction when we touch reality.

When a woman wanted to talk to me about her husband wanting to divorce
her, I didn't understand her incongruency in that she was smiling as
she described a marriage of 20 years falling apart. She smiled and
said, &quot;But I forgive him.&quot; I then asked her what he did to harm her
that warranted her forgiveness. At first she didn't know what say.
She was spellbound. She finally named all the times he had lied to
her, stepped out on her, verbally demeaned her, etc. By the time she
was finished, she was crying. A lot. During the sessions that
followed, she had to work through her feelings of anger, sadness,
shock, etc. By the time we were finished, she was able to say, &quot;I
forgive my husband. He owes me nothing. He will never be able to pay
me back for what he did to me.&quot; And she was then able to set the
boundary, in her case, of not allowing him to call her.

Another client , after she was molested when she was 8 years old, went
to a counselor a couple of times. It was only a couple of years ago at
age 20, that she told me the first thing the counselor told her was
that she had to forgive her perpetrator. She told me she hadn't been
able to get in touch with her anger because the counselor had made it
very clear that forgiveness meant &quot;Don't feel your pain, especially,
anger.&quot;

When I forgive someone it means I'm acknowledging I've been harmed.
When I get in touch with all that, I'm going to feel. And that's OK.

