Carla lady: So wonderful to hear your voice - well, your post is
close! I'd rather see you so I can give you a hug. Thanks for sharing.
Just got back from a Metro meeting. It was fun.

Phil and I have gotten into the habit of saying, &quot;I am wrong,&quot; when we
are. That helps US to take responsiblity for our behavior instead of
being flippant with the I'm sorry.

As for the &quot;I'm sorry,&quot; we might say, &quot;I was wrong. And I am apologize
for what I did.&quot; Sometimes we have said to each other after that,
&quot;Will you forgive me?&quot; and the response may be, &quot;I'm not ready to do
that yet. I have to process more.&quot; We give each other the space for
that. Demanding forgiveness is not appropriate and can cause damage.
One book I was reading awhile was about a man whose father had poured
acid on him when he was a kid. The only time the dad came back was
when he became a Christian. He told his son, a grown man by then, &quot;You
have to forgive me because I have to make my peace with God.&quot; WOW!
What crap. Another thing that bothers me is when someone says, &quot;I have
to forgive you because God commands it.&quot; Wow! That is really poor.
If that's why someone is forgiving me, please don't tell me that was
your motivation. If God were taken out of the picture, that wouldn't
be happening. I want REAL relationships - not ones that are based on
obligation.

By admitting we're wrong, instead of being flippant with the &quot;I'm
sorry's&quot; and &quot;I forgive you's&quot; makes for safe relationships. There
was a person in my life once, for example, who said she was sorry but
had no understanding of what she did wrong. Without that understanding
on her part, I knew she'd repeat the pattern. I wouldn't have been able
to handle a repeat performance. THere are others, like the person in
Carla's life, who aren't sorry at all and just flip the word out to
make them look good. (or whatever).

Good thoughts. Keep 'em coming!

(Carla, I'm happy for you. I really am.)

