Talking about movies that relate to the &quot;forgiveness&quot; theme.

Phil and I just saw &quot;Walk the Line&quot; - about Johnny Cash's life. I
really like Cash and I understand his &quot;dark&quot; history. I love his
realness. I had heard a few years ago that he and June Carter fell in
love after each had been married before; Johnny was married when they
met; they had seen each other at the same gig. &quot;Love at first site,&quot;
they have said in interviews. Interviews with the couple also stated
that their ex's and all the kids get together during holidays and have
a blast together. As you probably know, the Cash's died within 4
months of each other sometime last year or the year before. &quot;Soul
mates&quot; as some say. TRUE story.

When I read the article - before seeing the movie - I remembered
thinking how God's forgiveness DOES cover a multitude of sins. The
couple had sinned against their former spouses in many ways, fell in
love, eventually married and DID live happily ever after. They were
both Christians so no one can say, &quot;Well, they hadn't come to Christ
before they were married.&quot; Our Lord took this couple's sin - forgave
it, and then gave them a fulfilled life together.

I didn't know the entire movie would be about the Cash/Carter
relationship. As I sat there what came to mind was the many couples
I've counseled and friends who I've talked to who struggle with the
temptation to throw out their marriages because the &quot;grass is greener
on the other side.&quot; All these people I was thinking about are &quot;devout&quot;
Christians. Even though the movie was a beautiful example of a revived
life and the grace of God, I know it will be a temptation for some
people who watch it to CHOOSE to leave their spouses because, &quot;Look
what God did for the Cash's. No one was really hurt in the long run.&quot;
blah blah blah.

I left the movie with really mixed feelings. Loved the singing; Loved
Cash's ruddy, realness; loved that June Carter had loved him fully
regardless of his many screw ups and actually nursed him into recovery.
LOVED how the grace and mercy of our God was depicted. AND I was
saddened - devestated, in fact - thinking about families who have seen
the Lord's forgiveness toward a spouse who left them for another man or
woman and how much &quot;glory&quot; that movie depicted about the new
relationship.

What I'm trying to say is that our Lord's grace is not fair. He
forgives people who hurt us. And we have to deal with that and heal
and struggle with our faith in a God who could do that.

BUT, thank God He is not fair. All I have to do is look at myself and
realize that if He was fair, I'd be in hell - just like the Cash's and
the rest of us - for not being able to live a holy life.

I love to say to the person who has sinned, &quot;THe Lord will redeem you.
He will give you new life. That's what He's done for me - many times.&quot;

I love to say to the person who has to watch the Lord bless those that
have hurt them, &quot;I'll help you work this out. I'll be with you when
you feel the pain. And I'll pray that our Lord will make it clear to
you that he hasn't taken sides; that He's still with you and does not
negate your feelings of anger and pain simply because He has forgiven
the one that has wounded you so deeply. That's what He's done for me -
many times.

</POST>



