I'm on a role today. I'll keep writing.

I think, too, we flippantly throw out, &quot;God forgives you,&quot; or &quot;I am
forgiven by Jesus,&quot; without thinking about what we're saying.

When the Lord (or anybody) says, &quot;I forgive you,&quot; they are saying that
a crime has been committed against them. If harm had not been done,
there's no need to forgive. (I feel bad for people who think that they
have harmed every Tom, Dick and Harry because their self-esteem is so
low that they can't discern when they have actually harmed another and
need to make ammends.)

THink about it. I need to anyway. I am forgiven by Jesus. That means
I have harmed Him. He knows I have and He was willing to wipe the
slate clean - once and forever - when He shed His blood on that cross
so long ago.

WHen I'm in touch with the harm I've caused myself and others, hearing
the &quot;I forgive you always and forever&quot; from my Jesus, I want to cry and
hug Him and thank Him for wanting a relationship with me knowing full
well what I've done in the past and knowing full well what I'll
continue to do in the future.

It really IS inappropriate to simply throw around the word
&quot;forgiveness.&quot;

